<paragraph blockId="10.[182,1147,416,3264]" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">
Remarks. The larva was found together with many more of the same species, and with larvae of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Geijskes" baseAuthorityYear="1943" box="[245,693,2385,2422]" class="Insecta" family="Aeshnidae" genus="Triacanthagyna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentata">
Triacanthagyna 
<emphasis box="[557,693,2385,2422]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">dentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in several phytotelmata held by a fallen tree (see above under 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Pseudostigmatidae" genus="Microstigma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rotundatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">Microstigma</emphasis>
rotundatum
</taxonomicName>
for habitat description). An adult male had established its territory around the log and a second male was seen there as well, but none was taken.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[182,1147,416,3264]" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">
It is interesting to note that North of the Orinoco, in the Coastal Cordillera. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karsch. Only" authorityYear="1889" box="[799,1010,2752,2790]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Libellula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="herculea">
<emphasis box="[799,825,2752,2790]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[852,1010,2753,2790]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">herculea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
breeds in quiet portions of rocky quebradas (mountain creeks), but also in water-filled crevices of rocks which may be overflown periodically by the quebrada after rainfall. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karsch. Only" authorityYear="1889" box="[587,799,2964,3001]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Libellula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="herculea">
<emphasis box="[587,799,2964,3001]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">L. herculea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only Vene. zuelan dragonfly with a definite courtship display, which seems identical to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Selys" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1868" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Libellula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="croceipennis" subGenus="Belonia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="67">Libellula (Belonia) croceipennis</emphasis>
Selys
</taxonomicName>
, described by 
<bibRefCitation author="WILLIAMS, C. E." journalOrPublisher="Odonatologica" pageId="10" pageNumber="67" pagination="283 - 287" part="6" refId="ref10800" refString="WILLIAMS, C. E. 1977 - Courtship display in Belonia croceipennis (Selys), with notes on copulation and oviposition (Anisoptera: LibelluIidae). Odonatologica, 6. 283 - 287." title="Courtship display in Belonia croceipennis (Selys), with notes on copulation and oviposition (Anisoptera: LibelluIidae)" type="journal article" year="1977">Williams (1977)</bibRefCitation>
. Oviposition behavior is also identical.
</paragraph>
